<lb/><p>Man &amp; his brother = <persName>Bisa</persName>
<lb/>one went far to country
<lb/><persName>Mehera</persName> one foot one leg
<lb/>&amp; one eye one arm &amp;
<lb/>long hair - <add place="above">carried <persName>Mehera</persName></add> came to land
<lb/>of big <term type="insect">bees</term> - big <term type="animal">bird</term> - passed
<lb/>fire went around - <persName><choice><orig>bera</orig><reg>Bera</reg></choice></persName>
<lb/>went to fight &amp; when
<lb/>the people saw one-eye
<lb/>all died - came to a
<lb/>big <term type="animal">serpent</term> &amp; <term type="animal">serpent</term>
<lb/>said come on my
<lb/>back - which had
<lb/>fire inside - Kimbi
<lb/>or <term type="animal">buffaloes</term> &amp; all fled
<lb/>&amp; <term type="animal">Elephants</term> fled from
<lb/><term type="animal">serpent</term> - stones also
<lb/>were melted - came to
<lb/>one man &amp; all women
<lb/>of village brought forth - made<!-- "made" may belong to right-hand block - it is certainly physically located there but makes no sense there and could make sense in left block AM -->
<lb/><term type="animal">snake</term> of hot fountain
<lb/>All came to visit <term type="animal">serpent</term></p>
<lb/>
<!-- Heather I wasn't sure if this right-hand block should be included since it's not really part of any fable but looks like part of an account of a journey in search of the Nile, which starts on a previous page. However I transcribed it anyway, as best as I can AM -->
<!-- Theres also illegible writing (at least in this light) bisecting the transcribed passages. MBT -->
	<cb n="2"/>
<lb/><p rend="no-indent"><geogName type="lake">Victoria Lake</geogName> - and every
<lb/>step of their splendid <del type="strikethrough"><gap extent="1" unit="words" agent="illegible"/></del>
<lb/><del type="strikethrough"><gap extent="1" unit="words" agent="illegible"/></del> <add place="above">march</add> of following the
<lb/>river down took them
<lb/>further and further away
<lb/>from the head of the <geogName type="river">Nile</geogName>
<lb/>The idea that this lake which
<lb/>the <unclear cert="low"><term type="collective">Suaheli</term></unclear> assert to be three
<lb/>or four Lakes <unclear cert="low">was</unclear> into one
<lb/>huge Nyanza contained 20000
<lb/>square miles of water confused
<lb/>by sheer immensity - and
<lb/>then the little <geogName type="river">White Nile</geogName> that
<lb/>comes out of it less by a full
<lb/>half than the <geogName type="river">Shire</geogName> out of
<lb/><geogName type="lake">Nyassa</geogName> when <unclear cert="low">seen</unclear> to be
<lb/>unfit to account for the
<lb/><geogName type="river">Nile</geogName> but for devotion
<lb/>to the foregone conclusion
<lb/>they must have turned West</p>

	<pb facs="liv_000023_0084" n="0085"/>
	<cb n="1"/>
<lb/><!-- note that this line is only visible at end of page 84, and has been cut off at top of current page AM --><p rend="no-indent">&amp; gave food - stones
<lb/>became food 
<lb/>asked children from
<lb/>each - <unclear cert="low">Cyhere</unclear><!-- Ghere? MBT --> &amp; they
<lb/>Leaned on hill as
<lb/>a pillow - <persName>Kituku</persName>
<lb/>&amp; golakwa<!-- some overwriting here. Memory is fuzzy on how to do this: golak<del>q</del><add>w</add>a MBT --> -
<lb/><persName>Gong</persName> <term type="animal">tortoise</term>
<lb/><persName>Mache</persName> friend of his
<lb/><persName>Udrere</persName> was caught
<lb/>by trap mtegoa
<lb/>frozen - would
<lb/>not cut off fungi
<lb/>&amp; died then <persName>Gong</persName>
<lb/>became sultan
<lb/>on <choice><sic><term type="animal">serpent</term>s</sic><corr><term type="animal">serpent</term>'s</corr></choice> back
<lb/>&amp; is so till this
<lb/>day</p>
<lb/>
	<cb n="2"/>
<lb/><!-- see above comment about 2 unrelated blocks on same page - note that the transformation assumes they ARE related and runs them on continuously; also note that the 1st line is only visible at end of page 84, and has been cut off at top of current page AM --><p rend="no-indent">valley and there <unclear cert="low">found <gap extent="1" unit="words" agent="illegible"/></unclear>
<lb/>of ample <del type="cancelled">to</del> size to <unclear cert="medium">account</unclear> for
<lb/>the whole <geogName type="river">Nile</geogName> with all its <gap extent="1" unit="words" agent="illegible"/>
<lb/>and inundations.</p>
<lb/><p><persName>Sir S Baker</persName> came further up the
<lb/><geogName type="river">Nile</geogName> valley than any <unclear cert="low">other</unclear> in modern
<lb/>times and to the last had his face
<lb/>in the right direction for discovering
<lb/>the sources, but he turned when
<lb/>some seven <unclear cert="low">hours still</unclear> short
<lb/>of them - the second <term type="collective">Egyptian</term>
<lb/>expedition in <date when="1862">1862</date> made a great
<lb/>stride and then <persName>Peterson</persName> as compared
<lb/>with <gap extent="1" unit="words" agent="illegible"/> but it <gap extent="1" unit="words" agent="illegible"/> <add place="below"><seg type="metamark">^</seg></add> <add place="above">too</add> when
<lb/>around a thousand miles short
<lb/>of <unclear cert="low"><placeName>Mocaput</placeName></unclear> <geogName type="river">Nile</geogName> - Probably some
<lb/>may still uphold <persName>Speke</persName> <persName>Grant</persName> and
<lb/><persName>Baker</persName> as the Discoverers but no harm
<lb/>will be done for all improved maps
<lb/>will <choice><orig>shew</orig><reg>show</reg></choice> that their sources are from 500 to
<lb/>700 miles down the great <geogName type="valley"><geogName type="river">Nile</geogName> valley</geogName> and 
